PARAMYXOVIRUS INFECTION, BUDGERIGARS -UK (SUSPECTED) (02)
*********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Thu, 26 Jun 2003
From: Ian Brown <i.h.brown@vla.defra.gsi.gov.uk>
[We are very grateful to Ian Brown and Ruth Manvell for their following
expedient response to our enquiry. Mods. AS/CP].
To date 4 submissions from budgerigars showing this clinical condition have
been received at VLA Weybridge. From 3 we have isolated an apparently
non-haemagglutinating cytopathic agent on chick embryo primary cells and
Vero cells, but so far we have been unable to type/identify the agent. It
did not grow in embryonated eggs inoculated by the allantoic route. We are
working on characterisation: electron microscopy suggests there may be a
'paramyxovirus like agent' present. It seems extremely unlikely that the
causative agent is APMV-1, APMV-2, or APMV-3. Currently 9 types of avian
paramyxovirus (APMV-1 to -9) have been recognised and in some of these
there are a large number of subtypes. In the past APMV-1, APMV-2, APMV-3
and APMV-5 viruses have been isolated from naturally infected caged birds,
including budgerigars. Whilst in the past isolation of APMV-1, APMV-2, and
APMV-3 has always been relatively straight forward, APMV-5 has proved to be
more difficult.
--
Ian Brown/Ruth Manvell
Avian Virology
VLA-Weybridge
<i.h.brown@vla.defra.gsi.gov.uk>
